# Background

Content Security Policy (CSP) is a browser security mechanism that restricts where scripts, styles, images, and other resources may be loaded from.

A correctly configured CSP can significantly reduce the impact of Cross-Site Scripting attacks.

However, if trusted sources are themselves vulnerable or allow execution of attacker-controlled code, the CSP can be bypassed.

This lab demonstrates that CSP is only as secure as the domains it trusts.

---

# Reconnaissance

The search functionality reflected user input directly into the HTML response.

Testing with simple payloads confirmed that HTML injection was possible.

The response headers included a CSP similar to:

```http id="tvt2f2"
Content-Security-Policy:
script-src https://trusted-domain.example
```

This indicated that inline JavaScript was blocked but scripts from a trusted external source were allowed.

---

# Vulnerability Analysis

The reflected parameter accepted attacker-controlled HTML.

Although inline JavaScript was blocked by the CSP, one of the trusted external domains exposed a JSONP endpoint.

Because JSONP responses execute as JavaScript, an attacker could invoke the endpoint with a malicious callback function.

Since the browser considered the script to originate from a trusted domain, the CSP allowed its execution.

The application therefore became vulnerable despite deploying CSP.

---

# Attack Flow

```text
Attacker
    │
    ▼
Craft malicious URL
    │
    ▼
Victim opens link
    │
    ▼
Injected HTML loads trusted JSONP endpoint
    │
    ▼
Browser accepts script (CSP allows it)
    │
    ▼
Malicious callback executes
    │
    ▼
JavaScript runs in victim's browser
```

---

# Proof of Concept

Example payload:

```html
<script src="https://trusted-domain.example/jsonp?callback=alert"></script>
```

In the lab, the payload used the trusted JSONP endpoint provided by the allowed domain to execute attacker-controlled JavaScript.

